<h2 id="what-is">What Is a USCIS Biometrics Appointment?</h2>
<p>A biometrics appointment is a brief visit to a <strong>USCIS Application Support Center (ASC)</strong> where staff collect your fingerprints, photograph, and digital signature. This is a standard part of most USCIS benefit applications, including <SmartLink href="/adjustment-of-status">Adjustment of Status (I-485)</SmartLink>, <SmartLink href="/i-751-petition-remove-conditions">I-751 to remove conditions</SmartLink>, and employment authorization.</p>
<p>USCIS uses this biometric data to:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Run an <strong>FBI background check</strong> on your criminal history</li>
  <li>Verify your identity against existing government databases</li>
  <li>Create a biometric record linked to your immigration file</li>
  <li>Produce identity documents (like your green card) with your photo and fingerprints</li>
</ul>
<p>The appointment is not an interview. There are no immigration questions. It is purely a data collection step.</p>

<h2 id="when">When You Receive Your Biometrics Notice</h2>
<p>After USCIS receives and receipts your I-485 package, they mail a biometrics appointment notice (<strong>Form I-797C</strong>) to the address on your application. This typically arrives <strong>4–8 weeks</strong> after filing.</p>
<p>The notice shows:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Your name and receipt number</li>
  <li>The date, time, and address of your assigned ASC</li>
  <li>Instructions on what to bring</li>
</ul>

<div class="art-info">
  <strong>Keep your address updated</strong>
  <p>If you move after filing, update your address with USCIS within 10 days using Form AR-11 (free, online at uscis.gov). A biometrics notice sent to the wrong address can delay your entire case — and USCIS may treat a missed appointment as an abandonment if you don't respond.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="bring">What to Bring</h2>
<p>You only need two things:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Your biometrics appointment notice (Form I-797C)</strong> — printed or on your phone</li>
  <li><strong>A valid government-issued photo ID</strong> — passport is strongly preferred; driver's license or state ID also accepted</li>
</ul>

<div class="art-warn">
  <strong>Don't bring guests or children</strong>
  <p>ASC waiting rooms are small and staff-only areas require individual appointments. Unless a family member also has their own appointment at the same time, leave them at home. Children and guests are generally not permitted past the waiting room.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="process">What Happens at the ASC</h2>
<p>The appointment is quick and low-stress. Here's the typical sequence:</p>

<table class="art-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Step</th><th>What Happens</th><th>Time</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Check in</td><td>Show your notice and ID at the front desk; staff verify your appointment</td><td>2–5 min</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Wait</td><td>Brief wait in the waiting area until a technician is free</td><td>5–20 min</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Fingerprinting</td><td>All 10 fingers scanned digitally — no ink involved</td><td>5 min</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Photo</td><td>Digital photo taken by the technician</td><td>1–2 min</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Signature</td><td>Sign on a digital pad for your record</td><td>1 min</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Done</td><td>You're finished — no paperwork, no questions, no interview</td><td>—</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Total time in the building: typically <strong>15–30 minutes</strong>, including waiting. Some applicants are in and out in under 10 minutes at quieter locations.</p>

<div class="art-info">
  <strong>Can I go early?</strong>
  <p>Yes — most ASCs accept walk-ins for scheduled appointments if they arrive early. Showing up 10–15 minutes before your appointment time is fine. You can also sometimes walk in on a different day, though this is at the ASC's discretion.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="reschedule">Rescheduling — and What Happens If You Miss It</h2>
<p>Life happens. Here's how to handle scheduling issues:</p>

<h3>To reschedule</h3>
<p>Call the USCIS Contact Center at <strong>1-800-375-5283</strong> before your appointment date. Online rescheduling is not currently available for biometrics. Rescheduling does not negatively affect your case — it's common and expected.</p>

<h3>If you missed your appointment</h3>
<p>Contact USCIS immediately. In most cases, USCIS will schedule a new appointment. However, repeated missed appointments or a long delay in responding can result in a Request for Evidence (RFE) or, in extreme cases, a denial for abandonment. Don't wait — call the same day if possible.</p>

<div class="art-cta-mid">
  <h3>Next: the AOS Interview</h3>
  <p>Biometrics is just one early step. The bigger milestone is the in-person AOS interview — where both spouses appear and the officer reviews your relationship. Know what questions to expect.</p>
  <a href="/marriage-green-card-interview-questions" class="art-btn">AOS Interview Question Guide →</a>
  <a href="/adjustment-of-status-processing-time" class="art-btn-outline">See Full AOS Timeline</a>
</div>

<h2 id="after">What Comes After Biometrics</h2>
<p>After your biometrics appointment, USCIS processes the results in the background. You won't receive a notice confirming completion — it just happens. Meanwhile, your case continues:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>EAD / Advance Parole combo card</strong> — typically issued 3–6 months after filing; allows you to work and travel while I-485 is pending. See the <SmartLink href="/advance-parole">Advance Parole guide</SmartLink> for travel rules.</li>
  <li><strong>Background check processing</strong> — FBI name check and biographic screening run in parallel with other case processing</li>
  <li><strong>Interview notice</strong> — typically mailed 8–16 months after filing, scheduling your in-person appointment at the local USCIS field office</li>
  <li><strong>AOS interview</strong> — both spouses attend; officer reviews your <SmartLink href="/bona-fide-marriage">bona fide marriage</SmartLink> evidence and eligibility</li>
  <li><strong>Green card mailed</strong> — usually 2–4 weeks after a successful interview; either a <SmartLink href="/conditional-green-card">conditional (2-year) card</SmartLink> or a permanent (10-year) card depending on how long you've been married</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="art-faq">
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">What happens at a USCIS biometrics appointment?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Staff collect your fingerprints (all 10), a digital photo, and signature. The process takes 15–30 minutes. There are no immigration questions — it's purely data collection for background checks and identity verification.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">How long after filing I-485 is the biometrics appointment?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Typically <strong>4–8 weeks</strong> after USCIS receives your application. You'll get the appointment notice (Form I-797C) by mail.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">What do I bring to my USCIS biometrics appointment?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Your appointment notice (Form I-797C) and a valid government-issued photo ID — your passport is best. That's it.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">Can I reschedule a USCIS biometrics appointment?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Yes. Call USCIS at 1-800-375-5283 to reschedule. Rescheduling has no negative effect on your case. Online rescheduling is not currently available.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">What if I miss my biometrics appointment?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Contact USCIS immediately to reschedule. Repeated missed appointments can delay your case or lead to a denial for abandonment. Don't wait — call the same day if possible.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">Do both spouses need biometrics for Adjustment of Status?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Only the immigrant applicant (the person filing I-485). The U.S. citizen petitioner does not attend biometrics. Both spouses do attend the AOS interview together, which is a separate, later appointment.</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="art-cta-dark">
  <h2>Preparing for the full AOS process?</h2>
  <p>Biometrics is one of the easiest steps. The <SmartLink href="/adjustment-of-status">complete AOS guide</SmartLink> walks through every stage from filing to green card in hand.</p>
  <a href="/adjustment-of-status" class="art-btn-white">Full Adjustment of Status Guide →</a>
